Not quite sure I understand why, but curl seems to work -- somewhat -- for my particular use case.  It's slow, but it works, possibly due to a problem in the server listener or in curl... as tests independent of terminal-notifier show it is stilI slow.
As for wget vs. curl, I suspect the path issue has something to do with the fact that curl is native to Mac OS but wget was installed through either macports or brew.
Here's a working example with curl:
Terminal:
./terminal-notifier -message "Click me to notify the app" -title "Test App" -execute "curl http://localhost:9876/"
Node.js or node-webkit app:
var http = require('http');
http.createServer(function (req, res) {
    res.writeHead(200, {'Content-Type': 'text/plain'});
    console.log('Message received from terminal.');
    var response = {content: "Node.js app has received notification. 200 OK and all that stuff."};        
    res.end(response.content);
}).listen(9876);
Now, if we could get around these path issues, we could use something like the npm module ws to communicate with an embedded WebSocket server instead of an HTTP server! :)  
